default&#xa0;
default              
defaultChair:default May I welcome members of the public to this sitting of the Foreign Affairs Committee? This is the second of a series of one-off evidence sessions on 
defaultMiddle East
default issues. The first was held in December on 
defaultSyria
default, and we have other plans. This session will examine the current state of relations between 
defaultIsrael
default and the 
defaultOccupied
default 
defaultPalestinian
default 
defaultTerritories
default, the efforts of the international community to bring about an agreement, and the prospect for the 
defaultMiddle East
default peace process in 2014. 
default              
defaultMay I give a very warm welcome to Professor Manuel 
defaultHassassian
default, the head of the Palestinian Mission in 
defaultLondon
default? Professor, it is very good to see you again. You have been a generous host to us in the past when we have had meetings, so we are particularly delighted that you have accepted the invitation. 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default It is my pleasure, sir. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ1default 
defaultChair:default Would you like to say a few words by way of an opening statement? 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default As members of the Committee know, the year 2014 is declared by the UN as the international year of solidarity with the Palestinian people. We hope that this year will not simply be in support of maintaining the status quo; we would like to see positive action in the Palestinians having their own independent Palestinian state. As far as the Palestinians are concerned, we have been committed to the peace process for the past 20 years. As a matter of fact, we have accepted so many concessions, starting with the acceptance of the state of 
defaultIsrael
default over 78% of the Palestinian historic territory, and so far there has been no acknowledgement of our nationhood or our statehood from the Israeli side. We want this peace process to succeed because we gain much, as Palestinians, from its success, for the simple fact that we could fulfil our national aspirations of having our independent state over 22% of historic 
defaultPalestine
default. Yet we are the ones who could really set a precedent for security, not only in our part of the world but in the entire 
defaultMiddle East
default region.
default              
defaultWe still do not know what 
defaultIsrael
default’s agenda is as long as it does not recognise Palestinian nationhood, and we are not really clear about 
defaultIsrael
default’s position in the peace process. We have seen preconditions coming into the actual, real negotiations, sponsored by the 
defaultUnited States
default. Secretary of State John Kerry is putting his whole heart into making this a success story. The Palestinian side has been very co-operative with Mr Kerry in making it a success story. However, we have not seen the Israelis after almost 20 rounds of talks; we are still just vacillating between borders and security and trying more or less to agree on semantics—what kind of security and borders we are talking about. 
default              
defaultWe do not have the maps that 
defaultIsrael
default wants really to share with us. We went there with the idea that the 1967 borders are the borders for a two-state solution in which two democracies could live side by side. So far I can say that the peace process is being stalled by the impediments being put by 
defaultIsrael
default and by the continuing Israeli settlements—the building of settlements. The 
defaultlatest was a couple of days ago. Prime Minister 
defaultNetanyahu
default has daringly announced that they will build another 1,400 units. Since 30 July last year, when we embarked on this new peace process, 
defaultIsrael
default has pledged to build more than 6,400 units on the West Bank and in 
defaultEast Jerusalem
default. Those are signs of a lack of commitment to the peace process as far as 
defaultIsrael
default is concerned. They are negative signs to our side that 
defaultIsrael
default is not serious about peace.
default              
defaultChair:default Thank you. I should have added at the beginning, professor, that we have just half an hour and a lot of questions, so please stay focused on the precise point being put to you.
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default You called me “professor”; as you know, professors tend to speak. If I were an ambassador, I would change my style. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ2default 
defaultChair:default I am the son of a professor and I know exactly what you mean.
default              
defaultDo you have the same feeling of urgency about the negotiations as Secretary of State Kerry had as he launched them? Is this the last chance for the two-state solution?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default I think it is the last chance for the two-state solution. That is why the Palestinians are taking these negotiations very seriously. We have been very co-operative with Mr Kerry. It is not only that the President is in direct contact with Mr Kerry, let alone the negotiating team, but I have managed to attend a couple of meetings with Mr Kerry. We have portrayed to him the total commitment of the Palestinians to non-violence with diplomatic efforts. We want the peace process to succeed and to have an independent Palestinian state. We have to finish with this occupation once and for all. We do not need crisis management. We want an end of conflict and an end of claims.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ3default 
defaultChair:default What are the implications if the talks do not succeed?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default The implications are many. First of all, the strategy of the Palestinians has always been a commitment to non-violence, so we are going to pursue our aims through non-violent means. It has been reiterated many times by President 
defaultMahmoud
default 
defaultAbbas
default that the path towards a solution is through negotiations, diplomatic efforts and non-violent means. But saying that does not mean that the President, myself or any authority could crush the tendencies of the frustrated—almost four and a half million Palestinians—so that they do not go to the street and start a new wave of a third intifada.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ4default 
defaultSir John Stanley:default Could you tell us how satisfied or not the Palestinian Authority is with the role and policies of the British Government towards getting meaningful negotiations under way between the Palestinians and the Israelis?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default In my opening remarks, I should have thanked the British Government for their total support to the Palestinians, not only politically, but economically, and their serious concerns about making this peace process a success story. We know through our private channels that the British Government have been working closely with Secretary of State Kerry and the American Administration in trying to push for a resolution to the conflict through peaceful efforts. Time and again we have heard Foreign Secretary William Hague saying that this is the last chance for a two-state solution. If we go to the 
defaultWest Bank
default today, we see that it is 
defaultdivided into four major cantons with no geographical continuity. With the building of the apartheid wall, with 
defaultGaza
default being totally separated and 
defaultJerusalem
default being isolated, there is no way that we could have our politically independent Palestinian state with this non-contiguous geographic entity, let alone with the building of settlements. It is not an encouragement to resolve this deal once and for all. 
default              
defaultGoing back to the question of the British Government, I think the British Government has been very committed to the peace process, and it has been very committed to helping Palestinian infrastructure development as well as promoting business with the Palestinians. It has always been committed in paying its contributions to peace efforts. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ5default 
defaultRory Stewart:default Thank you very much for coming. Given what you have said, it seems surprising that you still have confidence in a two-state solution. Why is that you came back to the negotiating table in July 2013? What gave you that optimism? 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default The PLO since 1988 has committed itself to the recognition of the state of 
defaultIsrael
default and to a two-state solution. In 1993, we reiterated our commitment to de jure recognition of the state of 
defaultIsrael
default, believing that the only way out of the conflict was through negotiation. However, 
defaultIsrael
default did not really comply with all the agreements that were signed, and it kept on building settlements and trying more or less to create settlement blocs with what they call natural expansion in those settlements. The continuation of that will be an impediment to striking a peace with 
defaultIsrael
default. As I mentioned earlier, if that process continues, the Palestinians will not be able to accept a two-state solution. 
default              
defaultThe principle stands that our commitment has been to a two-state solution. That has been the position of the PLO, as the interlocutor with the state of 
defaultIsrael
default. If you ask simple lay people and academics, looking at what is happening on the ground, it will be impossible to have a two-state solution with the current status quo. That is why we are still committed, as a Government, to a two-state solution, but we do not know what the future holds if 
defaultIsrael
default continues with the same expansionist policies. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ6default 
defaultRory Stewart:default Just looking at the repeated threats by negotiators on your side to leave the table, why have those repeated threats been made and what do you think their impact has been? 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default When you sit in a room and you keep talking about the same principles—
defaultIsrael
default came to the negotiations not discussing the substantive issues that were outstanding in the final status agreements. 
defaultIsrael
default continued to talk about two issues: security and borders. They have never shown the maps of what their borders should be. 
default              
defaultWe went to the peace process believing that there would be a Palestinian state eventually, through negotiations, on the 1967 borders, which were part of the international legitimacy and part of the UN resolutions. The frustration of the Palestinian negotiating team is that time and again, 
defaultIsrael
default talks about borders and tries to impose new ideas like, for example, having total security of the 
defaultJordan
default 
defaultValley
default and talking about a lease of 40 years, after which they would rethink sitting with the Palestinians for a joint security over the 
defaultJordan
default 
defaultValley
default. Such initiatives, at a time when we know exactly what the endgame is, and when we know exactly what Israel should have and what we have—injecting the idea of a Jewish state at this time when the negotiations are 
defaultabout permanent status issues is an attempt, more or less, to deflect the entire peace process into something else. That is where the frustration of the Palestinian negotiators is coming from. Nothing is moving forward with the Israeli side. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ7default 
defaultAndrew defaultRosindelldefault:default Professor, can you explain why the Palestinian Authority opposes the idea of accepting 
defaultIsrael
default as a nation state of the Jewish people? If the wording explicitly included equal rights for minorities, would that be acceptable?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default First of all, we have accepted the state of 
defaultIsrael
default, not the Jewish state of 
defaultIsrael
default. When you talk about a Jewish state, it implies two things for us immediately. One is the idea of negating the right of return for refugees, because by UN stipulations, they cannot go back to their original home, which today is in so-called 
defaultIsrael
default. Secondly, when you talk about a Jewish state, you are talking about an exclusive Jewish state, from which 1.5 million Palestinians holding Israeli citizenship are going to be banned. They will have to either be shifted into the 
defaultWest Bank
default or go to a third country. That is why the question of a Jewish state has a lot of implications for us. That is the first thing.
default              
defaultSecondly, why are we discussing a Jewish state at a time when we are still struggling to have our own borders set with 
defaultIsrael
default? Thirdly, I would say, let 
defaultIsrael
default start by changing its name by going to the United Nations. Why is 
defaultIsrael
default today not asking Jordan, with whom it has a kind of peace treaty, to recognise it as a Jewish state? Why not 
defaultEgypt
default, for example? Why is it mandatory that the Palestinians should give them that recognition? At the same time, how can we recognise an entity when we are not recognised by the contending party as an entity ourselves? They did not recognise us as the Palestinian nation state; why should we give them recognition of a Jewish state? After the end of these negotiations, when we come to a final agreement, I do not see any reason why we should not accept a Jewish state. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ8default 
defaultMr Roy:default Professor, what progress has been made to bring about greater unity between 
defaultGaza
default and the 
defaultWest Bank
default?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default We have never stopped the meetings between the Fatah faction and 
defaultGaza
default, but first I would like to make some general remarks. There is no division among Palestinians between 
defaultGaza
default and the 
defaultWest Bank
default. 
defaultGaza
default and the 
defaultWest Bank
default has been recognised internationally by the United Nations. It has been considered an occupied territory. We are one and the same. The Palestinian Authority has never stopped funding 
defaultGaza
default, even under the control of Hamas. Thirdly, Hamas is part and parcel of the Palestinian people. We are part of the same social fabric. If they have certain ideologies that we do not agree with, it does not mean that they are on the wrong side of the equation. 
default              
defaultWhat I am trying to say is that reconciliation is going to take place one of these days. Hamas has accepted giving the PLO the mandate to continue negotiations, and the result of those negotiations will be bound for a national referendum. In that respect, Hamas has not been an impediment to the peace process, and neither has it stopped the Palestinian Authority from meeting the Israelis and negotiating for peace, for that matter. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ9default 
defaultMr Roy:default When will elections take place? 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default Elections will take place as soon as we have reconciliation. Three kinds of elections are going to take place. One is legislative elections, because the Parliament has been dead for the last five years. Secondly, we will have presidential elections, and third, we will have Palestinian national council elections for the PLO. We hope that Hamas will participate in the three elections, representing the entire Palestinian social fabric. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ10default 
defaultMr Roy:default What work, exactly, has been done on agreeing these elections?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default There are some concerns from Hamas about going back to the quota system. They want, as in the national council of the PLO, which is our organisation in exile, 40% of the seats. That is not really acceptable, for the simple fact that elections need representatives of all kinds equally. There is no quota system. If there is a quota system, then there is no democracy or electoral process to start with. Of course, Hamas was in a situation where it was in total control of 
defaultGaza
default; it is still controlling it militarily. But as you know, with the developments in 
defaultEgypt
default and 
defaultSyria
default, Hamas’s political position is becoming very weak in 
defaultGaza
default. Hamas would not like to see elections held now, because they know that they would lose elections in 
defaultGaza
default. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ11default 
defaultChair:default Professor, 
defaultFathi
default 
defaultHamad
default, Hamas’s Interior Minister, claimed in a speech the other day that 
defaultIsrael
default would cease to exist by 2022. Do you distance yourself from those remarks? 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default I not only distance myself from those remarks, I categorically reject them.
default              
defaultChair:default Thank you. That is very helpful.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ12default 
defaultMr Baron:default Professor, we all know how important sound economics and economic prosperity are to any process—peace process or otherwise. As you are aware, there are proposals on the table from Secretary of State Kerry and the Quartet representative Tony Blair to secure something like $4 billion in investment for the Palestinians. Is it possible to make economic progress before a political breakthrough? If so, how important is it? Where does this fit into the big scheme of things? 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default This is a philosophical question: which comes first, the chicken or the egg? We have many differences over the issues of whether economic stability will bring political resolution to any kind of conflict. Or vice versa—if we have a political resolution then the economic development will basically pave the way towards more settlement, security and stability in the area. 
default              
defaultIt is important in our case that we should continually have economic development and try to secure that. The major problem today facing the Palestinian Authority is unemployment, as you know. I just came back from the West Bank three days ago and—my goodness gracious—the consumer goods in the West Bank are more expensive than in 
defaultLondon
default. Would you believe that? We talk about a per capita income ratio of one to almost 20, and we buy our goods basically from 
defaultIsrael
default. If you talk about the basic necessities, the Palestinians cannot really afford to pay for their basic necessities. 
default              
defaultI believe that economic development, yes, will try to create the ambience for stability and for the negotiations to succeed. But I would not say that it will be enough basically to maintain the status quo. We need to change the realities on the ground. Any kind of economic help would really give the momentum for the people to have hopes that they will cash very soon the dividends of the peace process.
default              
defaultIf we start with some kind of development, and let us assume that the negotiations are moving well in tag with that kind of economic development, then I think that would be a recipe for success. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ13default 
defaultMr Baron:default Thanks, Professor. On a related theme, can I move on to 
defaultBritain
default’s role in the peace process? 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default The Europeans’ role?
default              
defaultMr Baron:default No, the British, the UK Government’s role. You were very complimentary in answer to a previous question from Sir John Stanley about the role we have played so far. However, as has been mentioned in the House of Commons, in Parliament, a number of times, we talk about a peace process but there is very little peace and there is not much process, so more needs to be done. What more should be done, can be done, by the UK Government to drive the process forward, given that we all accept that we could be drinking in the last-chance saloon?
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default First, let me be a little bit blunt. With all our praise and acknowledgment to the British Government in supporting the Palestinians, not only the peace process but the Palestinians per se in the 
defaultOccupied
default 
defaultTerritories
default, we also have our frustrations with the British Government. Not recognising us as members of UNESCO was a total blow to me personally. I shouldn’t have seen such a position coming from the British Government while you have been very supportive of the Palestinians, let alone the issue of the Palestinians’ non-observer status in the UN, which was another frustration. 
default              
defaultI think the British Government are trying their best to help but I can see certain pressures coming from the Israeli and American side. I see that the British are there not as full partners in the political process. They are much more involved in paying the cheques rather than in playing an important role in the peace process itself politically. But yet we never undervalued the role of the British Government in putting pressures—low profile and discreetly—with the Americans through their own recommendations, let alone their tough position, especially on the issue of settlements. The British Government have been very outspoken on the question of the illegality of building Israeli settlements. 
default              
defaultThat is very encouraging for us as Palestinians, but we need the British Government to play a little bit more effectively on the political scene. They could put pressures on the Americans, for example, to put aside the question of the Jewish state. Let’s put those issues aside and deal with them at the end of the political process. The problem has always been the process and not the substance. Both parties know exactly what the endgame will be and what the political solution will be. Our problem has always been the process. When the rules of the game are being permanently and 
defaultdraconianly
default changed while we are engaged in a process, that is not an 
defaultencouraging gesture by the Israelis, so we would like the British Government to be more assertive and more affirmative in their position that the rules of the game should not be changed. You cannot change horses in the middle of the battle, and this is where we need you to be more proactive.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ14default 
defaultMr Baron:default A brief follow-up. You have described our role, perhaps accurately, as being more of a bystander than being proactive. If there were one, two, or perhaps three things that you would want to see changed in the 
defaultUK
default’s approach with regard to the negotiations and the peace process, what specifically would they be?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default First, continue with your position of saying that settlements are an impediment to peace. This is very important. Secondly, we would like you to continue to give warnings to your business people not to do business with illegal settlements. We are not talking about an Israeli boycott here. We are talking about illegal Israeli settlements that are selling products for $700 million to $1 billion. That is profit a year, and that in itself gives the Israelis the incentive to expand their settlements. Trying not to warn but to discourage business people—British people—to make deals with the Israeli settlements is something that we would really appreciate. Very much so.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ15default 
defaultMark defaultHendrickdefault:default Professor, in December last year, the European Council set out some conclusions that resulted in an offer of what they called an unprecedented package of European political, economic and security support to Israel and Palestine if they reach an agreement. What is the PA’s response?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default We opened our arms and we said we accept that. 
defaultIsrael
default has been lobbying the Europeans to improve the business guidance in its favour, and it has not stopped lobbying to change the rules of the association agreement. As far as we are concerned, we are really encouraged and we accept the fact that the EU has played a major role at least in economic development, but our frustration lies in the fact that it never had political teeth in the political process itself. So we have basically welcomed that package, but, of course, 
defaultIsrael
default is always trying to change the rules of the game and they always undermine the role of the Europeans, especially when it comes to the political part of the process.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ16default 
defaultMark defaultHendrickdefault:default Do you not see that this offer, which obviously has benefits for Palestinians, also has benefits for the Israelis in that it gives them a better status in terms of the trading relationship with the EU?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default 
defaultIsrael
default has to decide whether it wants peace or wants to continue with its activities. 
defaultIsrael
default so far has shown us a war agenda, not a peace agenda. If 
defaultIsrael
default continues to go with impunity, we are discouraged to see any kind of resolution. Denying Palestinians human rights and their rights for self-determination will exacerbate the situation to the point where violence will be inevitable. 
default              
defaultIf you ask me, in a nutshell, where do we stand in the negotiations, I can give you one sentence that has been my tagline for the last three years: we are stuck between the historically inevitable and the politically impossible.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ17default 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default We are coming towards the end of our allotted time, Professor, but I want to press you on the status of  
defaultEast Jerusalem
default. Will you tell us briefly about the importance that the Palestinian Authority attaches to the status of 
defaultEast Jerusalem
default and its availability to be the capital of a Palestinian state?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default First, East Jerusalem is considered to be an occupied 
defaultJerusalem
default, so when we talk about the West Bank and 
defaultGaza
default, we talk about 
defaultEast Jerusalem
default. We have never isolated 
defaultEast Jerusalem
default. We will never accept 
defaultJerusalem
default as being the undivided capital of the State of Israel. We have two solutions there. I have written extensively on the issue of 
defaultJerusalem
default, with 15 models of sovereignty through second-track negotiations. There is no time to discuss them, but our position, as the PLO and as the authority, is that without 
defaultEast Jerusalem
default there will never be an independent Palestinian state. That is number one. East Jerusalem and West Jerusalem should be part of an open city and the holy sites should be open to all faiths from all over the world, but if 
defaultIsrael
default decides to separate the city, the eastern part would be under our control and the western part would be under its control. 
default              
defaultAt Camp David, we accepted the fact that the Wailing Wall and the Jewish quarter would be ceded to the state of 
defaultIsrael
default as part of the continuation of the holy sites and religious rituals. We accepted that in a letter from the late Yasser Arafat to President Clinton. As you know, the 
defaultCamp David
default accords did not succeed for two reasons. First, 
defaultIsrael
default did not accept the right of return of refugees. Secondly, 
defaultIsrael
default wanted total political sovereignty over 
defaultEast Jerusalem
default. Those were the reasons why the peace process failed and why we had a second bloody intifada.
default              
defaultAs we stand today, 
defaultEast Jerusalem
default should be the capital whether open or not and that could be done. I have been working with Canadians on the issue of the internationalisation of the one square kilometre, which is the old city where we have all the religious sites, and on how an international body could control it, with the consensus of Israelis and Palestinians. There is much lateral thinking about how we can share the city of 
defaultJerusalem
default without building high walls between us and the Israelis.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ18default 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default Can I take you back to the right of return? You mentioned it a moment ago and in a little more detail earlier in our discussion. Do you accept that it is not now possible for there to be an absolute right of return and that some kind of compromise may be necessary, including, for example, financial compensation for those who might have that right in other circumstances but who cannot now exercise it for reasons of geography?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default First, let me say that the right of return is a legal, moral and individual right.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ19default 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default It is resolution 194 of the United Nations General Assembly, not of the Security Council.
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default Yes, I agree that it is not a Security Council resolution and that it is not legally binding, but it is still a resolution that came from the General Assembly. As I said, it is a legal, moral and individual right. Each Palestinian refugee is entitled to reparations and to the right to choose how his or her right of return should be implemented. The refugees have been 
defaultgiven meaningful options here. This is coming not only from my side as a Palestinian; it has also been discussed in the second-track negotiations. There are plausible solutions to the question of return.
default              
defaultIsrael
default has to accept the principle of return. In terms of pragmatism, which means choosing between constraints, we know for a fact that 7 million refugees are not going to come back, and 
defaultIsrael
default also knows that for a fact. Our red line of refugees is basically the 350,000 who are living in 
defaultLebanon
default, but not all of them would like to go back to their original homes, as you know. The options are as follows. First is returning to their original homes in what we call today 
defaultIsrael
default; the second is returning to the state of 
defaultPalestine
default. Third is naturalisation in host countries, and many of them have been naturalised. For example, our refugees in 
defaultJordan
default hold Jordanian citizenship. In 
defaultSyria
default, they hold Syrian identity cards. They have been naturalised in many countries, such as 
defaultCanada
default and 
defaultAmerica
default, but not 
defaultLebanon
default. Fourth is resettlement in a third country, such as if they opt to go to 
defaultCanada
default, the 
defaultUK
default or the 
defaultUS
default.
default              
defaultIn addition to all those options, the question of reparations must include restitution of property, which 
defaultIsrael
default is adamantly refusing, and compensation for material and non-material damage that was inflicted as a result of the forcible removal of the Palestinian 
defaultdiaspora
default following the 1948 war. There are solutions to the refugee issues. We should not take that as an impediment for a final settlement.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ20default 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default Finally, do you accept that land swaps may be a tool to be used not only in the overall settlement, but also in relation to a right of return?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default I have to be explicit with you: I was the top consultant for the late Faisal 
defaultH
defaultusseini
default, and in the year 2000 when we decided to go to 
defaultCamp David
default it was my team that came up with the idea of land swaps. Land swaps are important, if we first acknowledge that the borders are the 1967 borders. If there are minor rectifications
default 
defaultto be pragmatic—we agreed in Camp David that they should be equal in quality and quantity, consensual and accepted by both sides—land swaps could be a concession on the part of the Palestinians, and they could salvage Israel from getting into a deep confrontation with its own internal population, especially the upcoming war with the Israeli settlers if a decision is taken to dismantle the settlements. So yes, we agreed to land swaps at that time. We are reconsidering the question of land swaps, depending on the outcome of the negotiations. 
default              
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default I visited Orient House on a number of occasions and I met Faisal 
defaultHusseini
default. It is a matter of some regret to many of us that he is no longer with us. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ21default 
defaultSandra Osborne:default Can I ask about the human rights situation of the Palestinian people, in relation to non-violence? You have reiterated the PLO position on non-violence, but you have said that under certain circumstances violence is inevitable. The situation in 
defaultGaza
default is dire, as you know, and there is a lack of ability for economic development because of the blockade, etc. Do you think it is right that the tunnels should be destroyed? How do you think the people in 
defaultGaza
default are going to react if the peace talks fail, and do you think that Hamas will abide by a peaceful campaign?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default This needs a long answer.
default              
defaultChair:default I am afraid that you have one minute. 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default First, if there is peace with the Israelis, I think all issues will be resolved; but the opposition is nurtured by conflict and if there is no progress, the opposition could take that as an excuse to perpetuate its presence on the ground. That is what Hamas has been doing. 
default              
defaultWith the situation in 
defaultEgypt
default, the total crushing of the Muslim fundamentalists and all the tunnels being closed, Hamas is now precarious at best. It is in no position to make a political bargain, except accepting that the only way is to reconcile with Fatah and accepting the outcome of the negotiations. Hamas has no other choices. The military option for Hamas is no option at all. By the way, it is not Hamas that is instigating rockets against 
defaultIsrael
default: there are some Islamic jihadists, al-Qaeda members and extreme fundamentalists, which Hamas no longer controls in 
defaultGaza
default. They are the sources of tension now. That is why I say that if there is a breakthrough in the peace process, the situation will change on the ground and people will become more hopeful. 
default              
defaultNobody can control how people react to dire economic conditions. We saw that in the first and second intifadas. It was not political frustration that led to the intifadas, but the dire economic conditions. Now, with a package deal of $4 billion—the PLO has been investing almost half its budget in Gaza—and with a political process coming to fruition with the Israelis, with pressure put on by the United States, we can see a light at the end of the tunnel. 
default              
defaultBut I am not that optimistic, looking at the situation on the ground and trying to see, through leakage, what is going on in the negotiations between the Palestinians and the Israelis. There are no signs for us to be hopeful yet. We are emphasising that the peace process is the only way out, that there will never be a military solution to the conflict and that we have to exert all our strenuous efforts to make the peace process a success, but not at the expense of giving up our legitimate rights. 
default              
defaultChair:default Professor 
defaultHassassian
default, thank you very much indeed. 
default              
defaultProfessor defaultHassassiandefault:default Thank you, sir. It is my pleasure. 
default              
defaultChair:default Our time is up, but you can probably sense that the Committee is holding itself back, as indeed you have been. We could have gone on for at least another hour. Thank you very much indeed. We look forward to maintaining our contact with you.
