defaultIran
default and the conciliatory moves from the 
defaultUnited States
default towards it? What difficulty does that bring to formulating a peace process for the Americans in relation to 
defaultIsrael
default and the Palestinians? Does their mindset change the game?
default              
defaultProfessor Hollis:default I am one of the few people I know who is not criticising Obama for being weak. I think he—unlike some people—learned the lesson of 
defaultIraq
default. Had the Americans sought to lead some sort of intervention in 
defaultSyria
default at whatever stage, I think they would have ended up in the same situation as they did in 
defaultIraq
default. 
default              
defaultYezid
default may differ from me on that, but I am pretty clear and it is reinforced by what you just said. Intervention in any of these places is not an option that will turn things around. I therefore cannot think of anything more foolhardy than resisting an opportunity to get a negotiated deal with 
defaultIran
default. Of course it will not be 100% secure on whether they have a bomb in the basement, or the capacity close by, but I think it is mind-boggling that 
defaultIsrael
default should bounce the 
defaultUnited States
default into a war with 
defaultIran
default. So I think the position of the 
defaultUnited States
default has to be with the Israelis. We are determined that the region should not be destabilised by a nuclear-armed 
defaultIran
default and, if that takes some concessions for a one-off opportunity with President 
defaultRouhani
default, I am afraid you are going to have to put up with it.
default              
defaultProfessor defaultSayighdefault:default If I could add something, I think a comprehensive deal on the nuclear issue would be a tremendously positive thing for the region, but let us not assume that a de-escalation on that particular issue will necessarily change the dynamics of Iranian, Saudi or other competition. It is sort of like with the cold war: once we had established mutual assured destruction by the early ’60s, it did not prevent a lot of very destructive rivalry in the rest of the third world between the Soviet Union and the 
defaultUSA
default. 
default              
defaultWhen it comes to Israel and Iran, in particular, my feeling is—I base this on what people I know who are very close to the Israeli nuclear programme
default 
defaulthave been telling me for several years—that Israel can live with the sort of deal that seems to be on the cards now. I think Israel will come to terms with this, never mind what Netanyahu says, but that does not mean that, when it comes to Syria, Iraq, Lebanon or elsewhere, Saudis, Iranians and others will not still be competing, or even more so than before. 
